    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-21T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-21T22:00:00-05:00" n="513"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d513">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.111/430: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-22T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 22, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>656. Your November 10, 4 p.m.,<note n="9" xml:id="d513fn9">Not printed.</note>
                    travel in Honan. On November 18 the Embassy received the following undated
                    telegram from Chengchow: <pb facs="0430" n="424" xml:id="pg_424"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Missionaries strongly protest unwarranted order preventing crossing
                            river at Chenghsien. Travel safe (signed) Hoover, C. I. M.<note n="13"
                                xml:id="d513fn13">China Inland Mission.</note>”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>In note dated December 21 to the Minister for Foreign Affairs I urged that
                    restrictions on travel in Honan be enforced only when travel circumstances made
                    them necessary. I described the attitude of the Department as set forth in its
                    243 October 27, 7 p.m., and asked that appropriate telegraphic instructions be
                    sent to Chengchow authorities.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, Peiping. Repeated to Hankow, Tientsin by mail today.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
